Importing USGS Data

This section lays out the steps for importing data into R from the USGS database. This data is for the Tar River Basin in Pitt County, NC and spans 2015-2020.

  1. This line fetches the precip data from the USGS online database and the dates can be altered in the address.
rainYear = "https://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/nc/nwis/uv/?cb_00045=on&format=rdb&site_no=02084000&period=&begin_date=2015-01-01&end_date=2020-01-01"

2.This line fetches the discharge data from the USGS online database and the dates can be altered in the address.

flowYear  = "https://nwis.waterdata.usgs.gov/usa/nwis/uv/?cb_00060=on&format=rdb&site_no=02082585&period=&begin_date=2015-01-01&end_date=2020-01-01"

After the data is imported from USGS, the data must be formatted into tables for further use.

3.t1 is creating a table of the precip information from the database in which there are 7 columns, 6 of which are characters and 1 is a number. Skipping 30 lines allows the code to begin at the top of the table where the data begins

4.t2 is creating a table of the discharge information from the database in which there are 7 columns, 6 of which are characters and 1 is a number. Skipping 30 lines allows the code to begin at the top of the table where the data begins

t1 <- read.table(rainYear,skip=31,header=F, colClasses=c("character", "character", "character", "character", "character","numeric"), na.strings=c("NA", "-", "?", "***", "Eqp", "10s"))

t2 <- read.table(flowYear,skip=31,header=F, colClasses=c("character", "character", "character", "character", "character","numeric"), na.strings=c("NA", "-", "?", "***", "Eqp", "10s"))
  1. This renames the columns with titles that can be used in the future code and are better describers of the information in the column
daNames = c('agency', 'id', 'date','time','tz', 'prcp', 'flag')
daNamesFlow =  c('agency', 'id', 'date','time','tz', 'flow', 'flag')

#Application of the new column names to table 1
names(t1) = daNames
#Application of the new column names to table 2
names(t2) = daNamesFlow

Making Plots

1.Add all the data points every 15 seconds for one date together to create daily points of summed precipitation and discharge *Remember that which data sets are labeled t1 and t2

t1DailySum = aggregate(prcp ~ date, data = t1, sum)

t2DailySum = aggregate(flow ~ date, data = t2, sum)

1.1 The two databases can be combined into one table by their shared ID date

tall = merge(x = t1DailySum, y = t2DailySum, by.x = 'date', by.y = 'date')

2.open the ggplot library

library(ggplot2)
  1. Create a plot using the ggplot library which uses the sums of the daily precipitation. The axes are labeled and uses the bar chart format
p <- ggplot(t1DailySum, aes(x=date, y=prcp)) + geom_bar(stat="identity")
  1. Create a precipitation plot using the ggplot library which fills the bar chart with color and gives the plot a title and alters the y-axis limit
p <- p +ggtitle("2015-2020 Precipitation Data for the Tar River") + labs(y= "Precipitation, total, inches", x = "Years") + aes(fill = prcp) + ylim(0,3)
p

## Scale for 'y' is already present. Adding another scale for 'y', which will
## replace the existing scale.

5.Create a plot using the ggplot library which uses the sums of the daily discharge. The axes are labeled and uses the bar chart format

d <- ggplot(t2DailySum, aes(x=date, y=flow)) + geom_bar(stat="identity")
  1. Creating a plot using the ggplot library which fills the bar chart with color and gives the plot a title and alters the y-axis limit
d <- d + aes(fill = flow) +ggtitle("2015-2020 Discharge Data for the Tar River")+ labs(y= "Discharge, Total, Cubic Feet per second", x = "Years") + scale_fill_gradient(
  low = "skyblue",
  high = "navyblue")
d +labs(y= "Discharge", x = "Date")

## Scale for 'fill' is already present. Adding another scale for 'fill', which
## will replace the existing scale.

Improving Visuals

Creating an inverted plot of precipitation

q <- ggplot(t1DailySum, aes(x=date, y=prcp)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + scale_y_reverse()+ ylim(3,0) +ggtitle("2015-2020 Precipitation Data for the Tar River") + labs(y= "Precipitation, total, inches", x = "Years") + aes(fill = prcp) 
q
